<doc id="1191067" wikidata="Q2299100" url="?curid=1191067" title="Magnetic vector potential">
<text>In classical electromagnetism, magnetic vector potential (often called A) is the vector quantity defined so that its curl is equal to the magnetic field: formula_1. Together with the electric potential &quot;φ&quot;, the magnetic vector potential can be used to specify the electric field E as well. Therefore, many equations of electromagnetism can be written either in terms of the fields E and B, or equivalently in terms of the potentials &quot;φ&quot; and A. In more advanced theories such as quantum mechanics, most equations use potentials rather than fields.

Magnetic vector potential was independently introduced by Franz Ernst Neumann and Wilhelm Eduard Weber in 1845 and in 1846, respectively to discuss Ampère&#x27;s circuital law. William Thomson also introduced the modern version of the vector potential in 1847, along with the formula relating it to the magnetic field.

== Unit conventions ==
This article uses the SI system.

In the SI system, the units of A are V·s·m−1 and are the same as that of momentum per unit charge, or force per unit current.

== Magnetic vector potential ==
The magnetic vector potential, formula_2, is a vector field, and the electric potential, formula_3, is a scalar field such that:
formula_4
where formula_5 is the magnetic field and formula_6 is the electric field. In magnetostatics where there is no time-varying current or charge distribution, only the first equation is needed. (In the context of electrodynamics, the terms &quot;vector potential&quot; and &quot;scalar potential&quot; are used for &quot;magnetic vector potential&quot; and &quot;electric potential&quot;, respectively. In mathematics, vector potential and scalar potential can be generalized to higher dimensions.)

If electric and magnetic fields are defined as above from potentials, they automatically satisfy two of Maxwell&#x27;s equations: Gauss&#x27;s law for magnetism and Faraday&#x27;s law. For example, if formula_2 is continuous and well-defined everywhere, then it is guaranteed not to result in magnetic monopoles. (In the mathematical theory of magnetic monopoles, formula_2 is allowed to be either undefined or multiple-valued in some places; see magnetic monopole for details).

Starting with the above definitions and remembering that the divergence of the curl is zero and the curl of the gradient is the zero vector:
formula_9

Alternatively, the existence of formula_2 and formula_3 is guaranteed from these two laws using Helmholtz&#x27;s theorem. For example, since the magnetic field is divergence-free (Gauss&#x27;s law for magnetism; i.e., formula_12), formula_13 always exists that satisfies the above definition.

The vector potential formula_14 is used when studying the Lagrangian in classical mechanics and in quantum mechanics (see Schrödinger equation for charged particles, Dirac equation, Aharonov–Bohm effect).

In minimal coupling, formula_15 is called the potential momentum, and is part of the canonical momentum.

The line integral of formula_2 over a closed loop, formula_17, is equal to the magnetic flux, formula_18, through a surface, formula_19, that it encloses:
formula_20

Therefore, the units of formula_2 are also equivalent to weber per metre. The above equation is useful in the flux quantization of superconducting loops.

Although the magnetic field, formula_5, is a pseudovector (also called axial vector), the vector potential, formula_2, is a polar vector. This means that if the right-hand rule for cross products were replaced with a left-hand rule, but without changing any other equations or definitions, then formula_5 would switch signs, but A would not change. This is an example of a general theorem: The curl of a polar vector is a pseudovector, and vice versa.

=== Gauge choices ===
The above definition does not define the magnetic vector potential uniquely because, by definition, we can arbitrarily add curl-free components to the magnetic potential without changing the observed magnetic field. Thus, there is a degree of freedom available when choosing formula_2. This condition is known as gauge invariance.

Two common gauge choices are
* The Lorenz gauge: formula_26
* The Coulomb gauge: formula_27

=== Lorenz gauge ===

In other gauges, the formulas for formula_2 and formula_3 are different; for example, see &quot;Coulomb gauge&quot; for another possibility.

